Detailed Description

Base Class for all data decoders.

ORVDataDecoder provides a number of functions for all decoders and additionally defines a function that must be overloaded by derived classes: GetDataObjectPath();

virtual std::string ORVDataDecoder::GetDataObjectPath (  )  [pure virtual]

Every decoder must overload this to return a path in the xml header.

For example, if the dataId is located under 

          <key>dataDescription</key>
          <dict>
          ...
              <key>AnObject</key>
              <dict>
              ...
                  <key>DataFromObject</key>
                  <dict>
                      <key>dataId</key>
                      <integer>9909</integer>
      
          ...
then GetDataObjectPath() would return "AnObject:DataFromObject". It automatically searches in the dataDescription dictionary and automatically adds the dataId key.

Implemented in OR1DHistoHistogramsDecoder, ORAcqirisDC440Decoder, ORAD3511ADCDecoder, ORAD413ADCDecoder, ORAD811ADCDecoder, ORADC2249ADCDecoder, ORAmi286Decoder, ORBasicDataDecoder, ORBocTIC3Decoder, ORCaen775tdcDecoder, ORCaen785adcDecoder, ORCaen792qdcDecoder, ORCaenV260Decoder, ORCaenV265Decoder, ORCTITempDecoder, ORDataGen1DDecoder, ORDataGenTestData1DDecoder, ORDGF4cEventDecoder, ORDGF4cLiveTimeDecoder, ORDGF4cMCADecoder, ORGretaDecoder, ORGretaMarkIVDecoder, ORHeaderDecoder, ORIP320ADCDecoder, ORIP408DigitalIODecoder, ORJAMFADCDecoder, ORKatrinFLTEnergyDecoder, ORKatrinFLTEnergyHistogramDecoder, ORKatrinFLTWaveformDecoder, ORL2551ScalersDecoder, ORL4532channelTriggerDecoder, ORL4532mainTriggerDecoder, ORLakeshore210Decoder, ORLC950ScopeDataDecoder, ORMCA927Decoder, ORMksPdr2000Decoder, ORNPLpCMeterDecoder, OROrcaRequestDecoder, ORRunDecoder, ORScriptDecoderForRecord, ORShaperShaperDecoder, ORTDC3377tdcDecoder, ORTek220ScopeDataDecoder, ORTek754DScopeDataDecoder, ORTrig4ChanDecoder, ORTrigger32ClockDecoder, ORTrigger32LiveTimeDecoder, ORTrigger32GTID1Decoder, and ORTrigger32GTID2Decoder.

virtual std::string ORVDataDecoder::GetDictionaryObjectPath (  )  [inline, virtual]

This function allows us to grab a hardware dictionary from the header.

Some records include a hardware dictionary residing in the xml header that is static information associated with the hardware such as parameters, timing, etc. If this function returns a non-zero sized string, then OrcaROOT will search for all the cards that fit this parameter. See the description for Hardware access functions.

Reimplemented in ORAcqirisDC440Decoder, ORDataGen1DDecoder, ORDGF4cEventDecoder, ORDGF4cLiveTimeDecoder, ORGretaDecoder, ORGretaMarkIVDecoder, ORMCA927Decoder, and ORShaperShaperDecoder.

const ORVDictValue * ORVDataDecoder::GetValueFromKey ( std::string  key,
UInt_t  crate,
UInt_t  card 
) [protected, virtual]

Hardware dictionary access functions.

Usage is as follows. If a hardware dictionary exists and is found (using the name specified in GetDictionaryObjectPath()) then a Decoder may call Get[type]ValueFromKey[Array]. The key refers to the name of the parameter within the dictionary. For example, 

        <key>ObjectInfo</key>
        <dict>
                <key>Crates</key>
                <array>
                        <dict>
                                <key>Cards</key>
                                <array>
                                      <dict>
                                              <key>Card</key>
                                              <integer>0</integer>
                                              <key>Class Name</key>
                                              <string>ORVmecpuModel</string>
                                      </dict>
                                      <dict>
                                              <key>Class Name>
                                              <string>ORGretina4Model</string>
                                              <key>CFD Delay</key>
                                              <array>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                                      <integer>63</integer>
                                              </array>
                                              <key>CFD Fraction</key>
                                              <array>
                                                      <integer>0</integer>
                                                      <integer>0</integer>
       ...
To access the Gretina4 dictionary, GetDictionaryObjectPath() would return "ORGretina4Model". To grab the CFD Delay for index 0, one would call GetIntValueFromKeyArray("CFD Delay", CardOf(record), CrateOf(record), 0)

Other access functions work similarly.

void ORVDataDecoder::Swap ( UInt_t *  dataRecord  )  [virtual]

Handles swapping of record.

ORVDataDecoder::Swap() is called when data not matching the endianness of the host machine comes in. By default, Swap() swaps all of the long words. If this is not needed, or something different is needed, please overload it in a derived decoder. Swap does (and should) not touch the first long word since this is already handled in ORVReader.

Reimplemented in OR1DHistoHistogramsDecoder, ORAcqirisDC440Decoder, ORAD3511ADCDecoder, ORDGF4cEventDecoder, ORHeaderDecoder, ORJAMFADCDecoder, ORL4532mainTriggerDecoder, OROrcaRequestDecoder, ORScriptDecoderForRecord, ORTDC3377tdcDecoder, and ORVBasicADCDecoder.
